  "prompt": "What does each term in \"public static void main(String[] args)\" mean?",
  "response": "Let's break down each term in the \"public static void main(String[] args)\" method signature:\n\n1. \"public\":\n- Access modifier\n- Means the method can be accessed from anywhere\n- Allows the Java runtime to call this method from outside the class\n\n2. \"static\":\n- Means the method belongs to the class itself, not to any specific instance\n- Can be called without creating an object of the class\n- Allows the method to be run directly by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM)\n\n3. \"void\":\n- Return type of the method\n- Indicates that the method does not return any value\n- The method performs actions but doesn't send back a result\n\n4. \"main\":\n- Standard name for the entry point of a Java program\n- The JVM specifically looks for a method named \"main\" to start executing the program\n\n5. \"(String[] args)\":\n- Method parameter\n- \"args\" is an array of String arguments\n- Allows command-line arguments to be passed when running the program\n- Can be used to receive input parameters when launching the application\n\nExample:\n```java\npublic class HelloWorld {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        System.out.println(\"Hello, World!\");\n    }\n}\n```",
